Thorax
. Prothorax: Completely black or pale above notopleural suture; see 
Figs. 115–116
for morphology; propleuron black, sometimes with pale medial spot on ventral margin. Pterothorax: with diffuse green metallic reflections over dark colouration on mesepisternum and mesepimeron, can be completely black or with pale areas as follows: mesepisternum entirely black (
Figs. 164, 166
) to black with narrow pale line above mesopleural suture, line can be complete in hyaline wing males but more often restricted to spot (as in 
Fig. 162
) or discontinuous line on posterior third in both morphs (as in 
Fig. 163
), in hyaline wing males or young back-tipped males pale markings can extend forming a continuous line on anterior margin and middorsal carina (as in 
Fig. 32
); mesinfraepisternum usually with pale posteroventral spot (as in 
Fig. 169
), in darker individuals completely black (as in 
Figs. 164–166
); mesepimeron chiefly black, sometimes with narrow pale line below mesopleural suture on posterior third (as in 
Figs. 164
, 
167
), this line usually reduced to pale spot on mesopleural fossa (as in 
Figs. 165–166
); second line highly variable, two-tenths of width of metepisternum, fairly uniform along its length, and not reaching antealar carina (as in 
Figs. 164–166
), or in some populations widening up to half width of metepisternum above metathoracic spiracle, then narrowing again posteriorly (as in 
Figs. 162
, 
168
) in Tapalapa population up to half width of metepisternum at lower end and then widening uniformly to posterior eight-tenths, then narrowing after metapleural fossa (as in 
Fig. 169
); metepimeron highly variable, usually with pale line below the metapleural suture two-tenths width of metepimeron, then widening to half width next to antealar carina, thus forming L-shaped area posteriorly (as in 
Figs. 32
, 
164–166
),in the Tapalapa population covering up to half the width of the metepimeron anteriorly and then widening uniformly to eight-tenths posteriorly, thus forming an elongated triangular pale marking (as in 
Fig. 169
) and narrow pale line above metapleural carina, these lines sometimes joining anteriorly by a very narrow line on the anterior margin of the metepimeron (as in 
Fig. 32
); metinfraepisternum with or without pale ventral spot; sternum usually with black stripes parallel to metapleural carinae; legs pale but coxa usually with diffuse markings on meso- and metacoxae; femora usually with dim dark markings on extensor surfaces and black rings at distal ends (those marks can be reduced to diffuse spots); tibiae usually with diffuse dark marks along their entire surface; tarsi usually light brown to black; claws reddish.
